Hey guys! Just wanted to offer a tip for getting the green tip you want. 
Buy any 5.56 ammo you can find and use a small bottle of testers green model car paint to paint the tip green.
Seriously, I talked to my brother in NC and he told me that some guys have been caught doing that exact thing to make money of off the penetrator scare. So my "REAL" tip is be wary of the ammo you buy !!! make sure you didn't buy it form someone who has a hobby making model cars.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Czech VZ-24 w/ German Waffenampts
postcontent:
This doesn't really fit into my collection right now, so I figure I'll see what kind of interest there is. 

This is a German-marked and produced VZ-24.  From the research I've done and information I've been able to find, this rifle was produced shortly after Germany obtained control of Czechoslovakia.  As they took control of the country, they also took control of the arsenals and weapons plants.  This rifle is a product of that.

You can see the German proof marks pictured.  From what I've found, this is a predecessor to the German G24(t) that was produced in the Czech plants.  The Germans used up the parts in stock, then switched over to the German design.   This appears to be in the first year of production, first run of 10K of the German produced rifles in Czechoslovakia being built in 1941. The subsequent runs of 10K had a suffix to the SN.

The bolt and stock do not have matching serial numbers. I obtained it in a trade with the sporter stock (included and pictured) and put it back into it's original form with a replacement stock (not SN matched, either) and metal.  Both stocks go with this rifle.

Open to trades and offers.  Willing to ship to C&R or FFL for actual cost of shipping.  I have a C&R, so I will request a bill of sale.

TURPENTINE - a Universal Healer

Turpentine has been used medicinally since ancient times and are still being used as folk remedies up to the present. They were used in ancient Babylon to treat stomach problems, inflammations and ulcers. The process was first described in the ninth century in Persia.

A recent study in Nigeria found that about 70 per cent of the population used natural products medicinally. The most common applications are for infections and infectious diseases, autoimmune diseases, cancer, arthritis and rheumatic diseases in general. 

Turpentine distilled from different varieties of California pines is almost pure heptane, as in light petrol. Other varieties of pine produce mainly chemicals called terpenes, as present in fragrant oils.

Turpentine: Another Cure-all Therapy

In addition turpentine was previously used as a cure-all. Natural turpentine, commonly sold as "pure gum turpentine", was commonly used in lower doses. It was especially treasured for its antiseptic and diuretic properties and as a treatment for intestinal parasites. According to Wikipedia: "Turpentine was a common medicine among seamen during the Age of Discovery, and one of several products carried aboard Ferdinand Magellan's fleet in his first circumnavigation of the globe."

To expel tapeworms, a powerful dose of one to two tablespoons of turpentine was given, usually mixed with the same amount of castor oil and taken floating on  milk. This was repeated every second or third day until the fragments of the worm ceased to appear in the stool. For children, the prescription was less drastic: one teaspoonful of sugar, three to four drops of turpentine and one teaspoonful of castor oil.

title: For Sale/Trade:  25 ACP BERNARDELLI VP VEST POCKET PISTOL
postcontent:
1958 Bernardelli-Gardone V.T. Italia- Cal 6.35 BRE. VP (Vest Pocket). This is an older well made Italian Semi-Auto 25 ACP in Good Condition. Gun functions perfectly and is a nice little piece for a collection. I have the original box and paperwork from December1958 including the first original bill of sale to the original purchaser in 1959

Bernardelli entered into the gun business in 1631 first making barrels in Gardone Val Trompia, Brescia Italy. In 1865 Vincenzo Bernardelli founded the company which still exist today. In the 1920's Bernardelli also manufactured componets for Alfa Romeo aircraft engines. In the 1930's they made an Italian service revolver know as the System Bodeo, Model 1889. They are also known for crafting very high-end shotguns. After World War II, Bernardelli introduced its first self-loading pistol, the VP (Vest Pocket) Model, which was based on the Walther Model 9.

The Bernardelli VP is a very small blowback-operated striker-fired .25 caliber (6.35 mm) pistol with a barbell-shaped takedown latch at the rear. It has a full length slide that covers the 2" barrel, with an external extractor on the right side, an internal connector on the left side; a 5 shot magazine that incorporates a magazine safety.

title: For Trade:  SIG P220 45ACP
postcontent:
I am retired Navy and carried the 1911, Glock, and Browning Hi Power while on active duty. I've discovered I'm just not a DA/SA decocker kind of guy.

I had assumed it was a stainless model, however, after speaking to the Custom Shop Director and Senior Gunsmith at SIG SAUER learned it is in fact a low-glare nickel variant of which very few were ever produced. As you can see it does not have the contrasting controls as the models produced today, instead it is all nickel.

It is super clean, functionally flawless, and remarkably accurate. No stains, scratches, or blemishes of any kind. If it is not a rare piece, it is certainly hard to find. Zero defects. Comes with hard plastic carry case and three factory mags.
